Bring a #medium saucepan{} of @water{100%ml} to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp}. Preheat
your #oven{} to 220°C. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).
Roughly chop the @tarragon{1/2}(stalks and all). Once boiling add the @salad potatoes{350}
to the boiling water and simmer until you can just slip a knife through them,
~{15-20%minutes}.

While the potatoes are boiling, pop the garlic in a #bowl{} with the @olive oil{2%tbsp}
(see ingredients for amount). Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and mix together.
Pop the @tenderstem broccoli{150} on a #baking tray{} and drizzle with @olive oil{2%tbsp},
season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and set aside. Heat a drizzle of oil in a #frying pan{}
on high heat. Once the oil is hot, lay in the @British streaky bacon{4%rashers} and
fry them until browned and crispy, ~{2-3%minutes} each side. Remove to a #plate{}
covered in #kitchen roll{} and set aside. Keep the pan - you'll use it later.

Once the potatoes are cooked, drain in a #colander{}. Drizzle a little @olive oil{}
on a baking tray and then pop the potatoes on the tray in a single layer. Carefully
make a cross in the top of each potato, then use a #fork{} to gently crush them.
Drizzle the garlicky oil over the potatoes, then roast on the top shelf of your
oven until crispy, ~{20-25%minutes}. Pop the broccoli onto the middle shelf for the
last ~{10%minutes} of potato cook time.

Pop your potato pan back on medium heat and add the @creme fraiche{75%g},
@tarragon{}, @vegetable stock powder{1}, @wholegrain mustard{1} and @water{}.
Stir together, bring to the boil. Reduce the heat to medium low and simmer the sauce
until slightly reduced, ~{4-5%minutes}. Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{},
then remove from the heat. If you've got any spare time, get your washing up done
at this point.

Once everything is just about ready, pop your frying pan back on medium high heat -
it should have some bacon fat in the pan to fry the fish in, but if not, add a
drizzle of oil. Once hot, add the @sea bream fillets{2} to the pan skin side down,
season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and cook until the skin is golden brown,
~{2-3%minutes}, then turn over and cook for a further ~{2%minutes}.

> Don't move the fish while it's cooking skin side down or you won't get a crispy skin!
> The fish is cooked when opaque in the middle.

Reheat the sauce if necessary. Serve the potatoes and broccoli on plates with the
fish alongside, drizzle over the sauce. Snap the crispy bacon and sprinkle over the
top. Enjoy!